    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a good start. But some people argue that judges shouldn't be making decisions like that and should stick only to procedural due process. How would you address that critique in the lesson so the students understand why substantive due process is the more important way to look at it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Critics argue that substantive due process allows judges to legislate from the bench, usurping the role of elected lawmakers. However, supporters argue that when fundamental rights are at stake, the judiciary must step in as a final guarantor of liberty against overreach. Without a substantive check, the government could impose authoritarian laws that erode basic human dignity without violating any existing procedure. Ultimately, it ensures that certain rights are inherent and inalienable, regardless of current legislative trends.",
      "source": "target",
