    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. I just want to make sure the kids don't walk away thinking the 'procedural only' view is a valid legal theory. Can you write a final summary for the lesson that explains why the procedural view is essentially insufficient for a modern democracy compared to substantive due process?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The procedural due process view is insufficient because it only ensures fair *processes*, not fair *outcomes*, leaving citizens vulnerable to unjust laws. Imagine a perfectly fair trial for an inherently unfair law—the resulting outcome is still wrong. Substantive due process is necessary because it protects the substantive *content* of our rights, ensuring the government doesn't even pass oppressive laws in the first place. In a modern democracy, protecting core liberties requires guarding both *how* laws are made and *what* those laws are.",
      "source": "target",
